{{Infobox NRHP | name = Wheeler No. 1 Oil Well | nrhp_type = | image = | caption = | nearest_city= [[Drumright, Oklahoma]] | coordinates = {{coord|36|00|01.67|N|96|35|59.57|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Oklahoma#USA | map_alt = Pointer indicates location of the site on the map of Oklahoma | map_caption = Location within Oklahoma | built = {{Start date|1912}} | architect OR builder = | added = March 14, 1983 | area = Less than {{convert|1|acre|ha}} | governing_body = Private | refnum = 83002083<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }}
The '''Wheeler No. 1 Oil Well''' was the first well drilled in the [[Drumright-Cushing Oil Field]] of northeast [[Oklahoma]], near [[Drumright, Oklahoma|Drumright]]. The success of the well, drilled in 1912 by [[Thomas Baker Slick, Sr.]], led to the development of the Cushing field and gave impetus to the early development of Oklahoma oilfields.<ref name=nrhpinv1>{{cite web|last=Carney|first=George O.|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination Form: Wheeler Oil Well No. 1|url={{NRHP url|id=83002083}}|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=7 May 2013|date=July 1980}}</ref> The Drumright-Cushing field would go on to produce 310,000 barrels of oil a day at its peak in May 1917.<ref name=aoghs1>{{cite web|title=Oklahoma’s King of the Wildcatters|url = http://aoghs.org/oil-and-gas-history/oklahomas-king-of-the-wildcatters/ |publisher=American Oil & Gas Historical Society |accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=eohc2>Weaver, Bobby D. [http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=CU008 "Cushing-Drumright Field,"] ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture'', Oklahoma Historical Society. Accessed February 23, 2016.</ref> The well made Slick's name as "King of the Wildcatters".<ref name=eohc1>Pittman, Kitty. [http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=SL005 "Slick, Thomas Baker (1883-1930,"] ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History and Culture'', Oklahoma Historical Society. Accessed February 23, 2016.</ref>
The well was financed by Charles B. Shaffer of Chicago, who hired Slick to drill wells at the Frank Wheeler farm using [[Drilling rig#Cable tool drilling|cable tool drilling techniques]], which could not prevent gushers or [[Blowout (well drilling)|blowouts]]. Three unsuccessful wells preceded the strike, which initially produced 400 barrels of high-grade oil a day from a depth of between {{convert|2319|ft|m}} and {{convert|2347|ft|m}}. Because no mechanism existed to control the flow, the oil was diverted into pits for collection and storage. The source of the oil was a sand zone in the Drumright Dome, a [[syncline]].<ref name= nrhpinv1 /> Slick attempted to keep the strike secret, hiring armed guards,<ref name=newson6-1>{{cite web|last= Day|first= Craig|title= Drumright Oil Well Nears Its Centennial | url = http://www.newson6.com/story/16996085/drumright-oil-well-nears-its-centennial | publisher = News on 6 | date =February 22, 2012|accessdate=7 May 2013}}</ref> but eventually revealed the well's success in April 1912.<ref name =eohc1/> A dugout built for the guards remains on the site, together with a commemorative plaque.<ref name = newson6-1 />
In time, the well's pressure subsided, requiring that the oil be pumped out of the well. The first pump was a two-cylinder gasoline-powered pump, later replaced by an electric drive. With the reduction in pressure the well was modified for [[Extraction of petroleum#Secondary recovery|secondary recovery]], using an early form of [[hydraulic fracturing]] called "sand fracturing."<ref name=nrhpinv1/> As of 1980 it produced about a barrel a day, pumping four hours a day. Oil came from three layers: the Layton layer at {{convert|170|ft|m}}, the Wheeler layer at {{convert |2300|ft|m}}, and the Bartlesville layer at {{convert|2700|ft|m}}. A {{convert|2|in|cm|adj=on}} pipeline connects the well to an oil-water separating unit about {{convert|2500|ft|m}} away, then to storage tanks. The well is located in a small clearing about {{convert|1000|ft|m}} west of Drumright.<ref name=nrhpinv1/> The well was still producing in 2012.<ref name=newson6-1 />
The Wheeler No. 1 well was placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on March 14, 1983.<ref name = "nris" />
